<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="137" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="137">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="137">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schillhammer" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Hesperosoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hesperosoma guizhouense" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guizhouense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">Hesperosoma guizhouense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does not differ externally from two allopatric species, 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. klapperichi" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="klapperichi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">H. klapperichi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. alexpuchneri" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="alexpuchneri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">H. alexpuchneri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but it may be distinguished only by the shape of the aedeagus (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 73–78" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figures 73 - 78. Hesperosoma guizhouense 73 - 74 habitus 75 - 77 aedeagus, lateral (75) and ventral (76) views, paramere (77) 78 female abdominal tergite X. Scale bars: 2 mm (73 - 74), 0.2 mm (75 - 78)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1075.75799.figures73-78" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/620018" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">73-75</figureCitation>
): paramere in 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. guizhouense" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="guizhouense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">H. guizhouense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with relatively deeper medio-apical emargination, in 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. klapperichi" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="klapperichi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">H. klapperichi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with relatively shallower medio-apical emargination and in 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. alexpuchneri" pageId="0" pageNumber="137" rank="species" species="alexpuchneri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="137">H. alexpuchneri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with acutely pointed apex. In one examined male specimen, the suture is reddish, which may be explained by the variability of the species.
</paragraph>
